1. Deep Technical Explanation
7.1 Risk Quantification for Defenders
Risk assessment in a SOC is not academic—it drives daily prioritization decisions. Here's how senior analysts apply it:
Step 1: Asset Identification and Classification
Asset Class	Example	CIA Priority	Criticality Score
Crown Jewels	Customer PII database, source code	C > I > A	Critical (10)
Business Critical	Email, ERP, financial systems	A > I > C	High (8)
Business Important	Internal wikis, development tools	A > I > C	Medium (5)
Public Facing	Marketing website, public docs	A > I > C	Low (2)
Step 2: Threat-Vulnerability Pairing
Not all vulnerabilities are equally exploitable. Analysts evaluate:
•  Threat Capability: Does the threat actor have the skills/tools to exploit this?
•  Exploit Availability: Is there public exploit code (CVE with PoC)?
•  Attack Complexity: Does exploitation require multiple steps or conditions?
•  Privileges Required: Does exploitation need admin access, or work from unprivileged?
Step 3: Impact Assessment
Impact Category	Measurement	Example
Financial	Direct theft, regulatory fines, recovery costs	$50M GDPR fine
Operational	Business interruption, SLA breaches	4-hour manufacturing halt
Reputational	Customer churn, brand damage	15% customer loss post-breach
Regulatory	Legal consequences, license revocation	PCI DSS compliance loss
Safety	Physical harm, loss of life	Medical device compromise
Step 4: Risk Calculation
Risk Score = (Threat Likelihood 1-10) × (Vulnerability Exploitability 1-10) × (Asset Criticality 1-10) × (Impact Severity 1-10) / 1000
SOC Application: Alerts affecting Critical assets (10) with High exploitability vulnerabilities (8) and Severe impact (10) score 800—immediate escalation. Alerts affecting Low assets (2) with theoretical vulnerabilities (2) score 4—routine handling.
