7.4 False Positive Analysis and Detection Tuning
False positives are the silent killer of SOC effectiveness. An analyst who investigates 100 FPs daily becomes desensitized and misses the 1 TP that matters.
FP Root Causes:
Category	Example	Mitigation
Overly broad signatures	Alerting on all PowerShell execution	Contextual rules: parent process, command-line entropy
Legitimate administrative activity	IT team using PsExec for maintenance	Asset tagging, maintenance window awareness
Third-party software behavior	Backup agents scanning entire file system	Application whitelisting, expected behavior baselines
Threat intel noise	IP reputations with high false positive rates	Multi-source correlation, aged-out IOCs
Misconfigured assets	Development servers with no security controls	Asset inventory, configuration management
Tuning Methodology:
1. Measure: Track FP rate per detection rule (target: <5% for high-volume rules)
2. Analyze: For FPs, identify common benign patterns
3. Refine: Add negative conditions (NOT parent process = services.exe)
4. Validate: Ensure tuning doesn't increase FN rate
5. Document: Record tuning decisions for audit and knowledge transfer
