1. Logging and Telemetry Considerations
15.1 The Visibility Foundation
You cannot defend what you cannot see. Comprehensive telemetry is the prerequisite for all subsequent detection and response capabilities.
Critical Log Sources by Layer:
Defense Layer	Essential Telemetry	Retention	Use Case
Network	Firewall logs, NetFlow, DNS queries, proxy logs	90 days minimum	Lateral movement, C2 detection, data exfiltration
Endpoint	Process creation, network connections, file modifications, registry changes	30 days hot, 1 year cold	Malware execution, persistence, privilege escalation
Identity	Authentication logs, privilege elevation, group membership changes	1 year minimum	Account compromise, insider threat, lateral movement
Application	Database queries, API calls, file access	30 days	Data access patterns, application abuse
Cloud	CloudTrail, Azure AD, GCP Audit Logs	1 year	Cloud misconfiguration, unauthorized access
15.2 The "Explicit Deny" Rule
Many organizations log success but not failure. This is catastrophic—failures are often the only signal of attacker activity.
Must-Log Events:
•  Failed authentication (all types)
•  Firewall denies (especially outbound)
•  File access denials
•  API authorization failures
•  Privilege escalation attempts (successful and failed)
Analyst Reasoning: A burst of failed logins followed by a success is a brute-force pattern. Failed logins alone suggest credential guessing. Both are valuable signals.
