1. Historical Incident: The Equifax Breach (2017)
18.1 What Happened
Timeline Reconstruction:
Date	Event	Detection Opportunity Missed
March 2017	Apache Struts vulnerability (CVE-2017-5638) disclosed	Threat intelligence on critical web framework vulnerability
March-May 2017	Equifax fails to patch vulnerable Struts instance	Vulnerability management process failure
May 13, 2017	Initial attacker access via Struts exploitation	Web application firewall logs (if properly configured)
May-July 2017	76 days of undetected attacker activity	Network segmentation failure allowed lateral movement
July 29, 2017	Security team notices suspicious network traffic	First detection—but 76 days late
July-August 2017	Forensic investigation confirms breach	Incident response activated
September 7, 2017	Public disclosure	Regulatory, legal, reputational consequences
Attack Chain:
1. Initial Access: Exploitation of unpatched Apache Struts (CVE-2017-5638)
2. Execution: Web shell deployment for persistent access
3. Persistence: Multiple backdoors established
4. Privilege Escalation: Credential theft from compromised systems
5. Lateral Movement: Unrestricted movement across flat network
6. Collection: Database queries extracting PII
7. Exfiltration: Encrypted tunnels to external infrastructure
8. Impact: 147 million records stolen; $1.4B+ total costs
18.2 How the Problem Was Investigated
Discovery Mechanism: Security staff noticed suspicious outbound network traffic from a specific web portal—essentially, a lucky observation rather than systematic detection.
Investigation Challenges:
•  Expired certificate: Internal traffic inspection had been blind for months due to expired SSL certificate
•  Log gaps: Inconsistent logging across environment hampered timeline reconstruction
•  Asset visibility: Unknown systems and dependencies complicated scoping
Forensic Findings:
•  Attackers had access to 48 databases
•  Multiple attack vectors were active simultaneously
•  Data exfiltration occurred in encrypted chunks over weeks
18.3 How It Was Contained and Solved
