1. Chapter Overview
This chapter descends from the strategic principles of Chapter 1 into the physical and logical machinery of computing. We strip away the abstraction layers that make computers usable—operating systems, applications, friendly interfaces—to reveal the raw reality that defenders must confront: electrical states, memory addresses, CPU instructions, and the precise mechanics of execution.
You will learn that a computer is not a magical black box but a deterministic machine that processes binary data through well-defined cycles. This knowledge is not academic curiosity. It is the foundation of malware analysis, memory forensics, reverse engineering, and the detection of fileless attacks that never touch the disk. When your SIEM shows a Base64-encoded PowerShell command, you will understand exactly what you're seeing and why the attacker chose that encoding. When your EDR alerts on "process hollowing" or "remote thread injection," you will comprehend the memory manipulation that triggered it.
We will explore how data is represented—from the bit level through binary, decimal, and hexadecimal—and why defenders live in hexadecimal. We will dissect the CPU's fetch-decode-execute cycle and examine how attackers hijack it through buffer overflows and return-oriented programming. We will map memory architecture (stack, heap, code segments) and trace how modern malware lives entirely in RAM, leaving no disk artifacts for traditional forensics.
By the end of this chapter, you will possess the technical foundation that separates analysts who follow playbooks from analysts who understand the adversary's capabilities at the hardware level. You will know why "fileless" does not mean "invisible," why memory dumps are the ultimate forensic truth source, and how CPU architecture choices create both vulnerabilities and detection opportunities.
————————
1. Why This Topic Matters
3.1 The Fileless Malware Reality
Modern advanced persistent threats (APTs) and ransomware operators increasingly avoid disk-based persistence. Tools like Cobalt Strike, Meterpreter, and PowerShell Empire execute entirely in memory, leaving no traditional "malware files" for antivirus to detect. According to industry reports, over 70% of advanced attacks now involve fileless techniques.
Without understanding memory architecture:
•  You cannot interpret EDR alerts about "suspicious memory allocation"
•  You cannot analyze memory dumps for forensic evidence
•  You cannot distinguish legitimate PowerShell usage from malicious encoded commands
•  You cannot detect process injection techniques that bypass signature-based detection
3.2 The Forensic Imperative
When you discover a compromised system, you face a critical decision: preserve volatile memory or prioritize containment?
If you reboot the machine (common IT instinct), you destroy the most valuable forensic evidence—the attacker's code, injected DLLs, decrypted payloads, and live network connections that existed only in RAM. Understanding what lives where in memory determines whether you capture the smoking gun or destroy it.
3.3 Detection Engineering at the Hardware Level
Many high-fidelity detections rely on identifying "impossible" hardware behaviors:
•  Data Execution Prevention (DEP) violations: Code running from stack/heap (buffer overflow indicator)
•  Address Space Layout Randomization (ASLR) bypasses: Predictable memory addresses (exploit reliability)
•  Hardware-enforced stack protection: Return address corruption detection
•  Control-flow integrity: Unexpected jumps to attacker-controlled code
These detections require understanding CPU architecture, memory management, and the boundary between hardware-enforced and software-enforced security.
3.4 The Analyst's Advantage
Attackers operate at this level. When you understand binary encoding, you recognize that "TVqQAAMAAAAEAAAA//8AALgAAAAAQAA" is not random—it's Base64 for a Windows executable header (MZ). When you understand memory layout, you interpret Sysmon Event ID 10 (process access) as potential credential dumping from LSASS. This knowledge transforms opaque alerts into comprehensible attacker actions.
