1. Foundational Concepts
6.1 Why Defenders Live in Hexadecimal
Binary (base-2) is the machine's language. Decimal (base-10) is human-friendly. Hexadecimal (base-16) is the defender's compromise—compact like binary, readable like decimal, with trivial conversion between representations.
Conversion Table:
Decimal	Binary	Hexadecimal
0	0000	0
10	1010	A
15	1111	F
16	0001 0000	10
255	1111 1111	FF
256	0001 0000 0000	100
4096	0001 0000 0000 0000	1000
Why hex dominates forensics:
1. Compactness: One hex digit = 4 bits (one nibble). Two hex digits = one byte. FF vs 11111111 vs 255.
2. Alignment: Memory addresses, offsets, and byte values align cleanly. 0x00401234 is clearer than binary equivalent.
3. Pattern recognition: Experienced analysts recognize 4D 5A (MZ header), 7F 45 4C 46 (ELF), 89 50 4E 47 (PNG) instantly.
4. Tool output: Debuggers, hex editors, memory dumps all use hex. Fluency is non-negotiable.
SOC Application: When you see powershell.exe -enc TVqQAAMAAAAEAAAA//8AALgAAAAAQAA, you recognize Base64 encoding of binary data. Decoding reveals MZ header—this is an executable disguised as a command, not a script.
6.2 The Abstraction Ladder: From Transistors to Malware
Understanding where security controls live requires understanding the stack:
┌─────────────────────────────────────┐
│  Layer 7: Applications              │ ← Malware runs here (Word, PowerShell)
│  Layer 6: Runtime Libraries         │ ← API calls, standard functions
│  Layer 5: Operating System API      │ ← Syscalls, file operations
│  Layer 4: Kernel                    │ ← Memory management, process control
│  Layer 3: Firmware/BIOS/UEFI        │ ← Hardware initialization, Secure Boot
│  Layer 2: Instruction Set (x86/ARM) │ ← Machine code, registers
│  Layer 1: Microarchitecture         │ ← Pipelines, caches, speculative execution
│  Layer 0: Hardware (Transistors)    │ ← Spectre/Meltdown territory
└─────────────────────────────────────┘
Security implications:
•  Controls at higher layers are easier to deploy but easier to bypass
•  Controls at lower layers are harder to bypass but harder to update
•  Attackers operate at all layers; defenders must meet them at each
