The syscall gate: User-mode code (Ring 3) cannot directly access hardware or sensitive kernel structures. It must invoke system calls—controlled transitions to Ring 0. This boundary is the foundation of process isolation and security monitoring.
EDR hooking: Security tools intercept syscalls at the boundary between Ring 3 and Ring 0, monitoring requests before the kernel executes them. Attackers attempt to bypass these hooks through:
•  Direct syscalls: Bypassing user-mode hooks by calling kernel directly
•  Syscall unhooking: Restoring original syscall tables
•  Kernel callbacks: Operating at same privilege as EDR drivers
