7.2 The Stack: Structure and Exploitation
Stack frame anatomy:
High addresses
┌─────────────────────────┐
│  Return Address (RIP)   │ ← Target of overflow
├─────────────────────────┤
│  Saved Base Pointer     │
│  (previous RBP)         │
├─────────────────────────┤
│  Local Variables        │
│  [buffer]               │ ← Overflow starts here
│  [int x]                │
├─────────────────────────┤
│  Function Parameters    │
│  (if not in registers)  │
├─────────────────────────┤
│  ...                    │
Low addresses  ← Stack grows downward (toward lower addresses)
Buffer overflow mechanics:
void vulnerable_function(char *input) {
char buffer[64];           // 64-byte buffer on stack
strcpy(buffer, input);     // No bounds checking!
// If input > 64 bytes, overflow overwrites:
// - Saved RBP (64-71)
// - Return address (72-79)
// Return address now points to attacker-controlled code
}
Modern mitigations and bypasses:
Mitigation	Mechanism	Bypass Technique
Stack canaries	Random value checked before return	Information leak to reveal canary
DEP/NX	Stack marked non-executable	Return-oriented programming (ROP)
ASLR	Random base addresses	Information leak, partial overwrites
CFG	Validates indirect call targets	COOP (Counterfeit Object-Oriented Programming)
Shadow stack (CET)	Hardware copy of return addresses	Not yet widely bypassed
