Detailed: Process Hollowing (Modern Malware Favorite)
1. Create suspended process: CreateProcess("legitimate.exe", ..., CREATE_SUSPENDED, ...)
2. Unmap legitimate code: NtUnmapViewOfSection(hProcess, baseAddress)
3. Allocate memory: VirtualAllocEx(hProcess, ..., PAGE_EXECUTE_READWRITE)
4. Write malicious code: WriteProcessMemory(hProcess, ..., shellcode, ...)
5. Update entry point: Modify PEB (Process Environment Block) to point to malicious code
6. Resume execution: ResumeThread(hThread)
Detection artifacts:
•  Process created in suspended state, then resumed with modified memory map
•  Parent-child process anomalies (e.g., svchost.exe spawning from unusual parent)
•  Memory permissions: PAGE_EXECUTE_READWRITE in legitimate process
•  Section hashes: Disk image ≠ Memory image (hollowed process)
7.4 Memory Forensics: The Volatile Truth
When a system is running, the most complete picture of attacker activity exists in RAM. Memory forensics captures this state.
What lives in memory:
•  Running processes: Including hidden/rootkit processes
•  Network connections: Active sockets, connection state
•  Encryption keys: Decrypted for use; recoverable
•  Malware code: Fileless payloads, injected DLLs, unpacked executables
•  Credentials: LSASS process contains authentication material
•  Command history: PowerShell, cmd.exe buffers
•  File caches: Recently accessed file contents
