1. Practical Walkthroughs
Walkthrough 1: Magic Byte Forensics
Scenario: User reports "invoice.pdf" won't open. Security suspects malware.
Investigation:
Step 1: Check with file command
$ file invoice.pdf
invoice.pdf: PE32 executable (GUI) Intel 80386, for MS Windows
Step 2: Hex dump of header
$ xxd invoice.pdf | head -3
00000000: 4d5a 9000 0300 0000 0400 0000 ffff 0000  MZ..............
00000010: b800 0000 0000 0000 4000 0000 0000 0000  ........@.......
00000020: 0000 0000 0000 0000 0000 0000 0000 0000  ................
Step 3: Verify MZ header
4D 5A = "MZ" = Windows executable magic bytes
PDF would start with: 25 50 44 46 = "%PDF"
Conclusion: File is executable masquerading as PDF. Quarantine, hash, submit to sandbox, check for similar files in environment.
Walkthrough 2: Base64 Decoding in SOC
Alert: PowerShell execution with encoded command.
Encoded command observed:
powershell -enc "UwB0AGEAcgB0AC0AUwBsAGUAZQBwACAALQBzACAAMQAwADsAIABJAE4AVgBPAEsARQAtAE0AbwBzAHMAQwByAGkAcAB0AA=="
