1. Historical Incident: Spectre and Meltdown (2018)
18.1 What Happened
The vulnerability: CPU speculative execution optimization leaked data across security boundaries.
Mechanism:
•  CPUs guess future instructions and execute them early (speculation)
•  If guess wrong, results discarded—but cache state changes remain
•  Attackers measure cache timing to infer "discarded" data
•  Can read kernel memory from user mode, bypassing all software protections
Variants:
•  Meltdown: Intel-specific; kernel memory read
•  Spectre v1: Bounds check bypass
•  Spectre v2: Branch target injection
•  Spectre v3a / v4: Rogue data cache load, speculative store bypass
18.2 How the Problem Was Investigated
Discovery: Google Project Zero, independent researchers (Graz University of Technology)
Investigation challenges:
•  Hardware vulnerability = affects all software patches
•  No single fix; mitigation required OS, firmware, compiler changes
•  Performance impact of mitigations (5-30% in some workloads)
18.3 How It Was Contained and Solved
Mitigations (not fixes):
Mitigation	Mechanism	Cost
KPTI (Kernel Page Table Isolation)	Separate kernel/user page tables	Context switch overhead
Retpoline	Software speculation barrier	Indirect branch performance
Microcode updates	CPU firmware changes	Requires reboot, compatibility issues
Site isolation (browsers)	Process per site	Memory overhead
18.4 Lessons Learned
1. Hardware is not trusted foundation: Security must consider microarchitectural state
2. Performance vs. security trade-off: Speculative execution optimized for speed, created vulnerability
3. Coordinated disclosure complexity: Multi-vendor, multi-platform fixes required months
4. Detection challenges: Exploitation leaves minimal forensic artifacts
